    culture:{title:"الرُّوتِين وَالحَيَاة -- Daily Life in the Arab World",body:"The Arab day is structured by five prayer times. The workweek runs Sunday-Thursday in most Arab countries with Friday as the holy day. The midday meal (al-ghada) is the main meal eaten with family. The afternoon rest (al-qaylula) is culturally valued in hotter climates. The evening is when social life picks up -- visiting, coffee, conversation. Time is relational: a coffee visit lasting 3 hours is considered exactly right, not too long.",tip:"Sabah al-nour (morning of light) responds to sabah al-khayr (good morning). Each greeting has an escalating poetic response -- masa al-full, masa al-ward (evening of jasmine, evening of roses). Arab time greetings layer poetry on top of politeness."},
