    culture:{title:"التَّقوِيم الهِجْرِيّ -- The Islamic Calendar",body:"Arabs use both the Gregorian calendar and the Islamic lunar calendar (التَّقوِيم الهِجْرِيّ). The Islamic calendar began with the Prophet\'s migration (الهِجْرَة) from Mecca to Medina in 622 CE. It has 12 lunar months beginning with the new crescent moon (الهِلَال). Because it is lunar, the Islamic year is 11 days shorter than the solar year, so Islamic holidays rotate through all seasons over about 33 years.",tip:"The holiest months: رَمَضَان (fasting month) and ذُو الحِجَّة (pilgrimage month). مُحَرَّم is the Islamic New Year."},
    youtubeId:"L6g7xTyiFFU",xp:118,
    desc:"Command time in Arabic — days of the week, months, and the three calendars of the Arab world: Hijri, Gregorian, and Coptic. Ordinal numbers (first, second, third) make dates come alive.",
