    culture:{title:"رُوتِين الحَيَاة العَرَبِيَّة -- Daily Life in the Arab World",body:"The Arab workweek traditionally runs Sunday to Thursday, with Friday (يَوْم الجُمْعَة) as the holy day. In Egypt, the weekend is Friday-Saturday; in Lebanon and Jordan, it aligns with the European weekend. The midday meal (الغَدَاء) is the main meal of the day -- eaten at home with family when possible. The afternoon rest (القَيْلُولَة = siesta) is culturally valued in hotter climates. The evening (المَسَاء) is when social life and business often pick back up.",tip:"Arabs say صَبَاح النُّور (morning of light) in response to صَبَاح الخَيْر (good morning). Each greeting has an escalating poetic response: صَبَاح الفُل، صَبَاح الوَرْد (morning of jasmine, morning of roses)."},
