    culture:{title:"الأَعْدَاد فِي الحَضَارَة العَرَبِيَّة -- Numbers in Arab Civilization",body:"Arab scholars gave the world the numerals we use today (0-9) -- what we call Arabic numerals (الأَرْقَام العَرَبِيَّة), developed from Indian mathematics and transmitted to Europe through Arabic. The concept of الصِّفْر (zero) was mathematically developed by Al-Khwarizmi (خَوَارِزْمِيّ) whose name gave us the word algorithm. الجَبْر (algebra) from his book Kitab al-Mukhtasar fi Hisab al-Jabr is still the foundation of modern mathematics.",tip:"In classical Arabic, the number 7 (سَبْعَة) is deeply symbolic -- seven heavens (سَبْع سَمَاوَات), seven circuits around the Kaaba, seven verses in Al-Fatiha. The phrase سَبْعَة بَحُور (seven seas) means everywhere. The number 40 (أَرْبَعُون) symbolises a long time: Moses wandered 40 years."},
