    id:17,title:"Ordering at a Restaurant",culture:{title:"آدَاب المَطْعَم — Restaurant Etiquette in the Arab World",body:"In Arab restaurants, it is common for the host (who invited) to pay for everyone — splitting the bill is unusual and can even be seen as stingy. Expect a spirited negotiation over who pays: لَا، أَنَا أَدْفَع (No, I'll pay!). Tipping is expected (10-15%). Food is often shared — ordering individual dishes and not sharing is considered odd. Start eating only after the eldest at the table begins, or when the host says تَفَضَّلُوا.",tip:"بِالهَنَاء وَالشِّفَاء — said after someone finishes eating, meaning 'may it bring you health and wellness.' The response: هَنِيئًا."},arabic:"الطَّلَب فِي المَطْعَم",
