    id:18,title:"At the Market — Shopping & Bargaining",arabic:"فِي السُّوق — التَّسَوُّق وَالمُسَاوَمَة",
    culture:{title:"المُسَاوَمَة -- Bargaining Culture",body:"Arab market culture is one of the great social institutions of the Arab world. Bargaining (al-musawama) is expected and enjoyed -- a buyer who accepts the first price is naive; a seller who starts at the real price misunderstands the game. The process: offer half, meet somewhere in the middle, seal with handshake and blessing. Egyptian microbus drivers call out destinations from the window; souk merchants display their finest goods at the entrance.",tip:"Baraka Allah fik (may God bless you) closes a successful purchase. La, wallahi ma aqdar (by God I cannot) is the theatrical refusal. Muqtani? (satisfied?) seals the final deal. Arabic commerce is theatre -- and that makes it wonderful."},
    youtubeId:"OVBq4mDQfx0",xp:128,
    desc:"The Arab souq is a world of colour, scent, and negotiation. Shop, ask prices, bargain politely, and describe quantities. Discover Arab commercial culture at its most authentic.",
