    id:23,title:"Reserving at a Hotel",arabic:"الحَجْز فِي الفُنْدُق",
    culture:{title:"السِّيَاحَة العَرَبِيَّة -- Tourism in the Arab World",body:"The Arab world contains extraordinary heritage sites: الأهرامات (Pyramids), البَتْرَاء (Petra), جَرَش (Jerash), القُدْس (Jerusalem), تَدْمُر (Palmyra). Hotel culture ranges from ultra-luxury (Dubai, Beirut) to budget guesthouses (الفَنَادِق الشَّعْبِيَّة). A hotel receptionist may offer you tea -- refusing politely is fine, but accepting once is appreciated. Negotiating the room price (المُسَاوَمَة) is normal in smaller establishments.",tip:"The phrase عَلَى الرَّاحِة (take your time / be comfortable) is said by Arab hosts to make guests feel at ease. Responding with شُكْرًا، أَنْتُم أَهْل الكَرَم is appreciated."},
