    id:24,title:"Renting & Leasing an Apartment",arabic:"اسْتِئْجَار الشَّقَّة وَالعَقَارَات",
    culture:{title:"سُوق الشَّقَق -- The Apartment Market",body:"In Cairo and Arab cities, renting typically involves the مَكْتَب العَقَارِيّ (real estate agent), who takes one month rent as commission. A lease requires: الإِيجَار الشَّهْرِيّ (monthly rent), التَّأمِين (security deposit, usually 2-3 months), sometimes a مُقَدَّم (upfront payment). Most apartments are either مَفْرُوشَة (furnished) or غَيْر مَفْرُوشَة (unfurnished). Negotiating the price is expected -- the asking price is rarely the final price.",tip:"Apartment ads list: دُور ثَالِث بِدُون مَصْعَد (3rd floor, no elevator). In Cairo, elevator absence significantly reduces the price. Key questions to ask: هَل المَاء وَالكَهْرَبَاء مَدْفُوعَة? (are water and electricity included?)"},
