    culture:{title:"الخِطَاب العَرَبِيّ الرَّسْمِيّ -- Formal Arabic Letter Conventions",body:"Arabic formal letters have highly standardised opening formulas absent from English. A letter to a respected person begins: فَضِيلَة الأُسْتَاذ / سَعَادَة المَدِير (Your Excellency the Professor/Director). Business correspondence uses: تَحِيَّة طَيِّبَة وَبَعْد (greetings and after that...). Closing: وَتَفَضَّلُوا بِقَبُول فَائِق الاحْتِرَام (please accept the highest respect). Social media in Arabic has created a new informal register, but formal writing still follows classical patterns.",tip:"The basmala بِسْمِ اللهِ الرَّحْمَنِ الرَّحِيم (In the name of God, the Most Gracious, the Most Merciful) opens most formal Arabic letters, books, speeches, and many everyday actions."},
