    culture:{title:"الأَعْدَاد وَالعِلْم -- Arab Contributions to Mathematics",body:"Arab mathematicians transmitted the decimal system from India to Europe, making modern science possible. Al-Khwarizmi (fl. 820 CE) whose name gave us \'algorithm\' developed zero as a mathematical concept. His book Kitab al-Mukhtasar fi Hisab al-Jabr gave us the word \'algebra\'. The House of Wisdom (Bayt al-Hikma) in Baghdad (8th-9th centuries) was the world\'s greatest library and translation center while Europe was in its Dark Ages.",tip:"Arabic number system uses Eastern Arabic numerals in many Arab countries: the Western Arabic numerals 0-9 we use globally are a simplified version developed in Moorish Spain (al-Andalus). Numbers 1-10 open the door to all of Arabic arithmetic."},
