    culture:{title:"الأَعْدَاد وَالرَّمْزِيَّة -- Numbers and Symbolism",body:"Numbers carry deep cultural weight in Arabic. Forty (al-arbaun) symbolises a long journey -- Moses wandered 40 years, mourning lasts 40 days. Seven (al-sabaa) is sacred: seven heavens, seven circuits around the Kaaba, seven verses in Al-Fatiha. One hundred (al-miaa) means abundance: miaa aam saada (a hundred years of happiness). One thousand (al-alf) means immeasurable: alf mabrook (a thousand congratulations).",tip:"Arabic expressions with numbers: saba marrat (seven times = many times). Miit marra (a hundred times = repeatedly). Alf shukr (a thousand thanks = deep gratitude). Numbers in Arabic blessings are almost always symbolic round numbers, not literal counts."},
