    culture:{title:"النُّجُوم العَرَبِيَّة -- Arab Celebrities and Soft Power",body:"Arab entertainment has produced global icons. فَيْرُوز (Fairuz) from Lebanon is arguably the most beloved voice in the Arab world -- her songs are played daily across all 22 Arab countries. عَبْد الحَلِيم حَافِظ (Abdel Halim Hafez, the Egyptian Nightingale) and أُمّ كُلْثُوم (Umm Kulthum) defined 20th-century Arabic music. Today, Mohammed Assaf (from Gaza, Arab Idol winner), Nancy Ajram, and Amr Diab bridge traditional and pop styles. Arab cinema (from Cairo, Beirut, and Casablanca) has centuries of storytelling behind it.",tip:"أُمّ كُلْثُوم concerts in the 1960s would halt the Arab world -- factories stopped, the streets emptied, and Egypt came to a standstill every first Thursday of the month for her radio broadcast. This is unparalleled in global musical history."},
