    comprehension:[
  {type:"mcq",q:"The jussive mood is signalled by which ending on the verb?",opts:["ـُ (ḍamma)","ـَ (fatḥa)","ـْ (sukūn — removing the short vowel)","ـِ (kasra)"],ans:2,exp:"The jussive (المَجْزُوم) removes the final short vowel: يَذْهَبُ (indicative) → يَذْهَبْ (jussive). Triggered by لَمْ، لَا النَّاهِيَة، and إِن."},
  {type:"tf",q:"اِمْرَأَة Haifa Wehbe is a Lebanese actress and singer.",ans:0,exp:"TRUE — هَيْفَاء وَهْبِي is Lebanese and is one of the Arab world's most celebrated pop singers and actresses, known across the Arab world."},
  {type:"mcq",q:"What distinguished Arab celebrities differ from Western ones according to the passage?",opts:["They only work in one country","Their fame crosses all Arab borders because of shared language","They work only in classical music","They are always from Egypt"],ans:1,exp:"The passage notes that Arab celebrities achieve pan-Arab fame (شُهْرَة عَرَبِيَّة شَامِلَة) because the shared Arabic language and satellite TV create a unified cultural space."},
  {type:"mcq",q:"Infer: Why would Egyptian actors be most widely understood across the Arab world?",opts:["Egypt has the most people","Egyptian dialect is the most widely understood due to its media dominance","Egyptian Arabic is identical to Fusha","Egypt is geographically central"],ans:1,exp:"Egyptian dialect (العَامِّيَّة المِصْرِيَّة) became the de facto pan-Arab dialect through decades of dominance in cinema, television, and music. Most Arabs can understand it even if they don't speak it."}
,
      {type:"fitb",q:"لَمْ أَذهَبْ — What mood is the verb in? (jussive / subjunctive / indicative)",blank:"مَجزُوم — jussive",opts:["مَجزُوم — jussive","مَنصُوب — subjunctive","مَرفُوع — indicative"],exp:"لَمْ triggers the jussive (مَجزُوم): the final vowel is cut (sukun or letter dropped)."},
      {type:"mcq",q:"Which triggers the jussive mood?",opts:["أَنْ","لَنْ","لَمْ","حَتَّى"],ans:2,exp:"لَمْ (past negation) and لَا النَّاهِيَة (prohibition) both trigger the jussive."}],
    grammar:[{
      title:"The Jussive Mood — المُضَارِع المَجْزُوم",
      type:"table",
      headers:["Trigger","Meaning","Change to verb","Example"],
      rows:[
        ["لَمْ","did not (past neg.)","ـُ → ـْ (sukūn)","لَمْ يَخْسَرْ (he did not lose)"],
        ["لَا النَّاهِيَة","don't! (prohibition)","jussive","لَا تَتَوَقَّفْ! (don't stop!)"],
        ["لِـ (indirect imp.)","let him/her...","jussive","لِيَعْمَلْ بِجُهْد (let him work hard)"],
        ["إِن (conditional)","if","jussive in both clauses","إِن تَجْتَهِدْ تَنْجَحْ (if you work hard, you succeed)"],
        ["Hollow jussive","middle vowel drops","يَقُولُ → يَقُلْ","يَكُونُ → يَكُنْ"]
      ],
      note:"The jussive removes the final damma (ـُ → ـْ sukūn). Triggered by: لَمْ (past negation), لَا النَّاهِيَة (prohibition), لِـ (indirect imperative), and إِن (conditional). Critical: hollow verbs in the jussive lose their long middle vowel: يَقُولُ → يَقُلْ; يَكُونُ → يَكُنْ. This mood is used constantly in authentic Arabic. ★ JUSSIVE DRILL: Change these to jussive: يَذْهَبُ، يَكْتُبُ، يَأْكُل، يَنَام. Then negate each with لَمْ. ★ CONDITIONAL DRILL: Complete: إِنْ تَدْرُسْ ___ (تَنْجَح in jussive)."
    }],
