    culture:{title:"السِّيَاسَة العَرَبِيَّة -- Arab Political History",body:"The Arab world has seen monarchies (مَلَكِيَّات), republics (جُمْهُورِيَّات), and a unique mix of both. جَمَال عَبْد النَّاصِر (Nasser) embodied pan-Arab nationalism in the 1950s-60s. أَنْوَر السَّادَات won the Nobel Peace Prize after the Camp David Accords. يَاسِر عَرَفَات led the Palestinian Liberation Organisation for decades. The Arab Spring (الرَّبِيع العَرَبِيّ) of 2010-2012 toppled leaders in Tunisia, Egypt, Libya, and Yemen, reshaping the region.",tip:"الوَحْدَة العَرَبِيَّة (Arab unity) has been an aspirational ideal since the 19th century. The United Arab Republic (UAR), a short-lived union of Egypt and Syria (1958-1961), was the closest the modern Arab world came to political unity."},
