    id:36, title:"Famous Arab Singers & Musical Heritage", arabic:"المُغَنُّون العَرَب وَالتُّرَاث المُوسِيقِيّ",
    culture:{title:"المُوسِيقَى العَرَبِيَّة -- Arabic Music",body:"Arabic music is built on the maqam (melodic mode) system -- 72 modes each carrying an emotional character. Umm Kulthum (1904-1975) is arguably the greatest Arab artist ever; her concerts would stop Egypt. Fairuz (b.1935) from Lebanon is the most universally beloved Arab voice -- played daily across all 22 Arab countries for 70+ years. Abdel Halim Hafez was Egypt\'s most romantic voice. These three defined 20th century Arab cultural identity.",tip:"Arabic music uses quarter-tones (rub al-tawn) -- notes between the Western semitones -- giving it that characteristic quality Western ears find exotic. This is not out-of-tune; it is a more emotionally precise palette. Listening to Umm Kulthum teaches you Arabic vocabulary and grammar through music."},
    youtubeId:"OVBq4mDQfx0", xp:138,
    desc:"Celebrate the golden voices of the Arab world — Umm Kulthum, Fairuz, Abdel Halim Hafez. Discover the untranslatable concept of طَرَب and how Arab music connects poetry, emotion, and identity in a way unmatched in world music.",
