    id:40, title:"Religion & Religious Minorities in the Arab World",culture:{title:"التَّنَوُّع الدِّينِيّ — Religious Diversity in the Arab World",body:"Arab Christians have been present since before Islam — Copts in Egypt, Maronites in Lebanon, Greek Orthodox in Syria. The Coptic Orthodox Church traces its founding to Saint Mark in Alexandria. Lebanon's government deliberately distributes power among 18 religious communities (الطَّائِفِيَّة السِّيَاسِيَّة). In Egypt, Muslims and Christians often celebrate each other's major holidays.",tip:"In Egypt at Easter: المَسِيح قَامَ (Christ is risen) → حَقًّا قَامَ. Muslims in Christian-majority neighbourhoods often participate in Easter greetings."}, arabic:"الأَدْيَان وَالأَقَلِّيَّات الدِّينِيَّة",
    youtubeId:"OVBq4mDQfx0", xp:138,
    desc:"The Arab world is home to Islam, Christianity, Judaism, and other faiths. This lesson explores the rich religious tapestry — Copts of Egypt, Maronites of Lebanon, Druze of the mountains — and the vocabulary of respectful interfaith conversation.",
