    comprehension:[
  {type:"mcq",q:"التَّمْيِيز (tamyīz) is always in which grammatical case?",opts:["Nominative","Genitive","Accusative","Jussive"],ans:2,exp:"التَّمْيِيز = specifier noun — always in the accusative (مَنْصُوب). It specifies what is being measured/compared: أَكْثَر نَشَاطاً (more active — نَشَاطاً in accusative), 20 طَالِباً (20 students — طَالِباً accusative)."},
  {type:"tf",q:"Diglossia means Arabic has only one spoken variety.",ans:1,exp:"FALSE — Diglossia (الازدواجية اللغوية) means Arabic has TWO LEVELS: الفُصْحَى (formal/written) and العَامِّيَّة (colloquial/spoken). They coexist with different functions — formal education, media = Fusha; home, street = dialect."},
  {type:"mcq",q:"According to the passage, what is the best strategy for Arabic learners?",opts:["Learn a dialect first","Learn Fusha first as it is the common root that unlocks all dialects","Learn both simultaneously from day one","Avoid Fusha as it is not spoken"],ans:1,exp:"The passage advocates learning الفُصْحَى أَوَّلاً (Fusha first) because it is the جِذْر المُشْتَرَك (common root) that enables understanding of all dialects. Once you know Fusha, dialects become variations."},
  {type:"ar",q:"ما الذي يجمع العربَ الفصحى والعامية في استخدامهم اليومي؟",opts:["لا يوجد شيء يجمعهما","الكتابة والتعليم والإعلام تجمعهم في الفصحى بينما البيت والشارع بالعامية","الفصحى تُستخدم دائماً والعامية اختيارية","العامية في التعليم والفصحى في البيت"],ans:1,exp:"جوهر الازدواجية: الفصحى للكتابة، التعليم، الإعلام، الخطاب الرسمي. العامية للحياة اليومية، البيت، والشارع. العربي الذي تعلّم جيداً يتنقل بين المستويين بطلاقة حسب السياق."}
,
      {type:"fitb",q:"عِندِي عِشرُونَ _____ — (twenty books — accusative singular tamyiz)",blank:"كِتَابًا",opts:["كِتَابًا","كِتَابٍ","كُتُبًا"],exp:"Numbers 11-99 require the accusative singular as tamyiz: عِشرُون كِتَابًا."},
      {type:"mcq",q:"What case does التَّمييز always take?",opts:["Nominative","Genitive","Accusative","It varies"],ans:2,exp:"The tamyiz is always accusative (مَنصُوب): e.g. عِشرُون طَالِبًا (twenty students)."}],
    grammar:[{
      title:"Al-Tamyīz — التَّمْيِيز (The Specifier / Distinction Noun)",
      type:"table",
      headers:["Type","Example","Translation","Notes"],
      rows:[
        ["After numbers 11+","خَمْسَة وَعِشْرُون طَالِبًا","25 students","singular accusative"],
        ["After comparatives","أَكْثَر نَشَاطًا","more active","specifying the comparison"],
        ["After اِمْتَلَأَ","اِمْتَلَأَ الوَادِي مَاءً","the valley filled with water","accusative"],
        ["After كَم","كَم كِتَابًا قَرَأْتَ؟","how many books did you read?","singular acc."],
        ["After مَا أَحْسَنَ","مَا أَجْمَلَ العَرَبِيَّةَ!","How beautiful Arabic is!","exclamation"]
      ],
      note:"The tamyīz (specifier) clarifies what is being measured, compared, or filled. It is always in the singular accusative (مَنْصُوب). It answers 'what kind/type?'. After numbers 11+, it specifies what is counted. After comparatives (أَكْثَر، أَقَلّ), it specifies the quality being compared. مَا أَجْمَلَ السَّمَاءَ! (How beautiful the sky is!) — this exclamatory pattern uses tamyīz. ★ TAMYEEZ DRILL: Identify the tamyīz in: اشْتَرَيْتُ عِشْرِين كِتَابًا، مَلَأْتُ الكُوبَ مَاءً، هَذَا أَكْبَر مِنْهُ سِنًّا. ★ FILL-IN: اشْتَرَيْتُ خَمْسَةَ عَشَرَ ___ (add: كِتَابًا or كُتُبًا — which is tamyīz?)."
    }],
