    id:55, title:"Autos, Transport & Getting Around", arabic:"السَّيَّارَات وَوَسَائِل النَّقْل",
    culture:{title:"النَّقْل وَالمُدُن -- Transport and Arab Cities",body:"Arab cities are extraordinary mixtures of ancient and ultra-modern. Cairo: taxis everywhere, Metro (المِتْرُو), مَيْكْرُوبَاص (microbus), and a 5000-year urban history. Dubai: driverless metro, 160km/h highways, futuristic skyline. Marrakech: donkeys in the medina alongside electric scooters. Arab urban transport reflects this tension between tradition and modernity. Traffic in Cairo (زَحْمَة القَاهِرَة) is legendary -- and Arabic insults in traffic are a genre of their own.",tip:"Egypt\'s microbus (المَيْكْرُوبَاص) system is entirely informal -- no schedules, no maps, destinations called out the window. Yet 10 million Cairenes use it daily with perfect efficiency. This is Arab collective improvisation (الارْتِجَال) at its finest."},
